<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-04-28T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-04-28T05:00:00-05:00" n="500" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d500">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">561.311D1/10: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Dawes</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-04-28T11:00:00+01:00">April 28, 1931—11
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received April 28—8:55 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>124. Your 107, April 27, 4 p.m.<note n="65" xml:id="d500fn65">Not
                                printed.</note> Ferguson says that no agenda has been prepared for
                            proposed Conference. In effect the Conference is simply a gathering of
                            the representatives of the wheat exporting countries to discuss whether
                            or not in the present situation it is worthwhile to try to form some
                            plan for the betterment of wheat market and if so what.</p>
                        <p>Ferguson will give me for transmission a full list of those who have
                            accepted invitations within a few days.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Dawes</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>